The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 12, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 11: New Delhi Television (NDTV) India Ltds initial public offering (IPO) will open for subscription on April 21 to raise about Rs 100 crore from the capital market. The company has received a nod from the Securities and Exchange Board of India for its domestic IPO, which would remain open for subscription for a week. The roadshows for the IPO would be held across the country beginning next week. The company plans to pre-pay loans of Rs 20 crore in 2004-2005 from the funds raised through the IPO.																								 Mumbai, April 11: Industrial Devlopment Bank of India (IDBI) has sought bids for appointing an end-to end IT solution provider which would select vendors to establish infotech infrastructure, including networking systems, at an estimated outlay of Rs 35 crore.																								 Mumbai, April 11: Videsh Sanchar Nigam Limited (VSNL) has received four STM-1s on the international long distance leg of i2i cable network after the takeover of Dishnet DSLs internet businesses. This will help VSNL recover the entire acquisition amount of Rs 270 crore in a year.																								 Mumbai, April 11: Foreign institutional investors (FIIs) have hiked their stake in Television Eighteen India Ltd (TV18) by 5.25 per cent to 16.01 per cent in the fourth quarter ended March 2004. 																								 New Delhi, April 11: Life Insurance Corporations Varishtha Pension Bima Yojana has garnered Rs 5,247 crore till February 2004, covering over 2.87 lakh senior citizens. Excluding this scheme, LICs market share stood at 87.22 per cent after it mopped up Rs 11,371 crore in premium income in April-February.
